<HEADLINE>
Food group Danone reports sales jump, optimism about China
business
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
French food group Danone reported a sharp sales jump in the first
quarter and said it was optimismtic a settlement could be reached
in a conflict with its Chinese partner Wahaha.Danone, the world
leader in dairy products and the second leading provider of
bottled water, said sales in the January-March period rose 18.7
percent to 3.76 billion euros (5.9 billion dollars) from the same
period last year, or 11.4 percent according to comparable data.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the sales spurt had been driven by its baby food
unit Numico, where sales on a comparable basis were up 18.8
percent at 683 million euros.
</P>
<P>
Danone said that this year it foresaw an increase in sales on a
comparable basis of between 8.0 and 10 percent, an improvement in
its operating margin and an increase in earnings per share of at
least 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Danone was showing a gain of 2.13 percent at 56.51 euros at mid-
day on the French stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
Managing director Emmanuel Faber said the group remained
"optimistic" that its differences with Wahaha founder Zong
Qinghou could be resolved.
</P>
<P>
"This will take more time than we had thought but we are
optimistic about the conclusion of a long-term agreement that
will meet our goals in developing the beverage business in
China," he told a conference call with financial analysts.
</P>
<P>
He added that "certain tensions had recently surfaced" and gave
no estimate of a date by which the matter would be settled.
</P>
<P>
Danone and Wahaha in December agreed to suspend a legal battle in
connection with an ownership feud over the Wahaha brand name and
to work out their differences through negotiations.
</P>
